name: David Sacks
tweet: Fair point. Use both frameworks if you want. ‚ÄúDefault alive‚Äù requires you to make revenue growth assumptions, which can be risky in a downturn. ‚ÄúDefault investable‚Äù requires you to understand VC criteria ‚Äî also subject to change, but largely ascertainable by talking to VCs.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
In summary, there are 3 states that are ok: 
1. Cashflow positive - always good obvi.
2. Cashflow negative but VCs are truly willing to finance that growth. (Be realistic about that.)
3. Low burn, long runway, fixing metrics to become 1 or 2.

Everything else a no man‚Äôs land.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Who should embrace the ‚Äúdefault alive‚Äù standard? Later stage startups with low growth rates. Eg, $100M ARR growing 50% YoY. This is now completely uninvestable by growth-stage VCs. These companies would be better off realigning to PE model. Become cashflow positive, then grow.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Remember that you can‚Äôt wait until the end of your runway to fundraise. 2 years of runway is really only 5-6 quarters to fix problems. 2.5 years of runway is much better ‚Äî 8 quarters to fix problems.

name: David Sacks
tweet: If you‚Äôre not currently investable, you‚Äôve got to give yourself adequate time to fix your metrics. Tinkering, experimenting, finding PMF ‚Äî all of that takes time. Fixing problems in the business is typically more successful with a lean team anyway.

name: David Sacks
tweet: You‚Äôve got to be realistic about whether you are investable. It takes mostly ‚Äúgreat‚Äù metrics, maybe one or two ‚Äúgood‚Äù ones, and no disqualifiers (‚Äúdanger zone‚Äù). We‚Äôve tried to be precise about what this means for SaaS startups.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
‚ÄúDefault alive‚Äù is almost an impossible standard for early-stage startups since it means being cashflow positive.

On the other hand, ‚Äúdefault investable‚Äù means that your metrics are good enough to raise another round in the current environment.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Startups: Instead of thinking about whether you are ‚Äúdefault alive‚Äù vs ‚Äúdefault dead‚Äù, think about whether you are ‚Äúdefault investable‚Äù vs ‚Äúdefault uninvestable.‚Äù üßµ

name: David Sacks
tweet: Incredible thread. To paraphrase one of Benchmark‚Äôs investing tests, US policymakers need to stop asking only what can go wrong with crypto and start asking what can go right. Let‚Äôs play to win, not play to lose.

name: David Sacks
tweet: William F. Buckley‚Äôs aphorism has never been more true: ‚ÄúI would rather be governed by the first 2,000 people in the telephone directory than by the Harvard University faculty.‚Äù

name: David Sacks
tweet: Only academic experts could fall for the colossal foolishness that debt doesn‚Äôt matter. Any regular person intuitively understands that you can‚Äôt keep borrowing forever.

name: David Sacks
tweet: At some point we must graduate from the gradual phase to the sudden/acute phase ‚Äî especially if policymakers believe we will always stay in the gradual phase and increase borrowing accordingly ‚Äî fully embracing the moral hazard.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Of course the US government can‚Äôt go bankrupt as long as it controls the money printer and its debt remains denominated in dollars. But we should understand that unprecedented levels of peacetime debt/GDP will cause unpredictable distortions and deleterious effects.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
Debt never seems to matter ‚Äî until it suddenly does. 

Hemingway described it well in The Sun Also Rises:

‚ÄúHow did you go bankrupt?‚Äù

name: David Sacks
tweet:
Deplatforming is already the attempt by people with power to control the supply side of the information flow. 

Manipulating the algorithm is how they control the demand side. But this censorship is even more insidious because it‚Äôs harder to see.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
Control the feed and you control the flow of information that the American public gets to see. 

The engagement algorithm, while not perfect, at least lets users decide what they see based on their own preferences.

name: David Sacks
tweet: To be clear, I could care less whether anyone or everyone deletes their Facebook account. What I object to is politicians whipping up a moral panic to create spurious authority to control newsfeed settings ‚Äî ie, the power to control the flow of information.

name: David Sacks
tweet: If Facebook is showing users bad stuff, it‚Äôs because those users indicated a preference for it. Just like rap lyrics. Just like video games. Just like sugar drinks. Just like your preferred media bubble. Just like your preferred partisan politician. Welcome to consumerism.

tweet: Eventually, every successful company needs to great at product, marketing, AND sales. But in the early stages, it‚Äôs hard to be great at everything. So Founder/GTM Fit ensures that the founder‚Äôs talent is aligned with a GTM motion they can be successful with.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Product founders trying to figure out an outbound motion, or sales founders trying to figure out bottom-up/product-led growth, generally doesn‚Äôt work as a strategy for getting to initial traction.

name: David Sacks
tweet: If you don‚Äôt have Founder/GTM Fit, then you either need to develop a new GTM or quickly become great at a new skill or add the missing cofounder.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
Founder/Go-to-Market Fit:

If primary GTM is bottom-up, founder needs to be great at product. 

If primary GTM is inbound, founder needs to be great at marketing. 

If primary GTM is outbound, founder needs to be great at sales.

name: David Sacks

7/ Bad cities/politicians will scoff at this analogy. They are too good for sales. They‚Äôve lost sight of their customer. They‚Äôre trapped in legacy thinking.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 6/ R&D - successful cities will plow ARR back into features that enhance the value of the city, creating a virtuous cycle that attracts more ARR. They will listen to customers about what those features should be, not special interests (who are basically suppliers, not customers).

name: David Sacks
tweet: 5/ Marketing - successful cities will track their NPS score and have an active presence on social media. They will define a vision, maybe even put forth a mission statement. They will understand and enhance their niche in a competitive market for knowledge workers.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 4/ CSM - successful cities will instrument churn, try to collect churn notes from people who leave, and work to eliminate the reasons for churn before it happens. They will view CSAT as their key metric.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 3/ Sales - successful cities will sell job creators on moving there. That‚Äôs why @FrancisSuarez is killing it right now. He‚Äôs selling unopposed. It‚Äôs pretty easy to win competitive deals when your rivals aren‚Äôt even bothering to counter-sell against you.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 2/ ARR - successful cities will view taxpayer revenue as an annually recurring subscription by residents who are free to cancel at any time. Accordingly they will try to delight customers, not vilify them. They will focus on delivering a product that people want.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 6/ Moral of the story: when a SaaS business has both B2B/Team plans and B2C/Individual plans, break your analysis into two separate buckets. If B2B has compounding cohorts and B2C has deteriorating cohorts, place all the value on B2B and view B2C as lead gen. //

name: David Sacks
tweet: 5/ How does Craft value a business like this? We placed 0 value on ARR from the Individual business but valued the Team business at a very high ARR multiple. We led the Series A. VCs that didn‚Äôt separate Teams vs Overall may have missed why we are so excited about this one.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 4/ Most importantly, revenue cohorts for the Team product were compounding over time whereas revenue cohorts for the Individual product were shrinking. This is the key point: The Team product was creating a growing revenue base while the Individual base was deteriorating.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 3/ The Individual plan had about 60% annual revenue retention, which is poor (but not uncommon for Individual plans). The Team product had roughly 200%+ net revenue retention, which is fantastic. https://t.co/ybUq6orBD3

name: David Sacks
tweet:
2/ Craft evaluated a Series A investment that had 85% annual revenue retention across the Overall business. It didn't look particularly impressive. 

But when we separated cohorts for Individual and Team plans, we saw a very different picture. The average masked two extremes.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
1/ This was a very interesting case study so it deserves its own little tweetstorm. 

Q: What is the proper way to analyze a SaaS company that has revenue from both Individual and Team plans?

Founders: I'm about to reveal a trade secret of Craft.

Other VCs: pease stop reading.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
7/ Hybrid strategies can make sense for B2B SaaS startups. Individual plans may not be a great long-term business, but they can be a great lead generation machine for the Team product. 

For more on Individual vs Team plans, read my new blog post:

https://t.co/HvclJLo0ls

name: David Sacks
tweet: 6/ Frankly I‚Äôm skeptical of valuations in B2C SaaS right now. Investors are paying B2B SaaS multiples on ARR without seeming to understand the difference between cohorts that are shrinking versus those that are growing every year. Day of reckoning may be coming.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 5/ The magic of B2B/Team SaaS is in those compounding cohorts. By contrast, B2C/Individual SaaS has shrinking cohorts. 50%/year revenue churn is not uncommon so the SaaS vendor is rebuilding its business from scratch every 2 years! Hard to build a very valuable company this way.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
4/ Third, Seat Expansion.

Team plans add new seats as the product spreads within a company, creating revenue expansion. As a result, successful Team products have ‚Äúnet negative churn,‚Äù meaning that expansion exceeds churn. 

E.g. this beautiful chart from Slack‚Äôs S-1: https://t.co/xkM3UDn0gh

name: David Sacks
tweet:
3/ Second, Retention. 

Team products are stickier than Individual products. Multiplayer mode is more engaging than single-player mode. And it's harder to leave. 

Account-level churn rates for Individual plans are typically 5% per month, but only 1-2% per month for Team plans.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
2/ First, Deal Sizes.

Team products have larger contract values (b/c multiple seats). Small CVs of Individual products often can't justify the cost of a sales team. Unless the Individual product is highly viral, it will be easier to build distribution for a Team product.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
1/ A common dilemma for SaaS founders is whether to focus on individual users or teams as the primary customer. This has important implications for pricing & packaging as well as product design. 

TLDR: Team plans are where the money is & where founders should focus. Here's why:

name: David Sacks
tweet: 9/ This is a brilliant acquisition for Salesforce, not just because it gives them a new cloud and an application hub, but because it gives them a way onto every seat in the enterprise. Slack justifies a true wall-to-wall license. This has been Benioff‚Äôs dream since Chatter.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 8/ Also note that Microsoft is not a latecomer to this party. They bought Yammer in 2012, ~2 years before Slack, in an effort to transition the Office franchise to cloud/social/mobile‚Äîan effort that eventually resulted in Teams. They were always going to be a tough competitor.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 7/ Just because Microsoft is a tough competitor, let‚Äôs not act like Slack ‚Äúlost‚Äù. Slack did a phenomenal job, created a massive outcome and would have been fine on its own. It was also up against the toughest bundle there is. Being part of Salesforce bundle does help level that.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
6/ In addition to sales, a bottom-up SaaS startup has to get earned marketing right. Use your early logos to consolidate the perception of category leadership before incumbents can react. ‚ÄúThe one who defines the category wins the category.‚Äù

https://t.co/kZTglzrZkU

name: David Sacks
tweet: 5/ Slack eventually got this right but the initial anti-sales mentality did cost them some time. Let‚Äôs put this in context: they had ~7 years of otherwise flawless execution. But still, the sooner that product-first SaaS founders embrace sales, the better off they will be.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
4/ Thus it‚Äôs incumbent on the startup to quickly convert bottom-up traction into deals. Bottom-up is great for top-of-funnel but you still need a sales team to close. Enterprises don‚Äôt self-serve. This was a central learning of Yammer. 

https://t.co/B2IscQ1e7S

name: David Sacks
tweet: 3/ Bottom-up works best for new categories of software. Once IT makes a wall-to-wall decision, it settles the matter. In other words, bottom-up works best when there‚Äôs no top-down. Nature abhors a vacuum. In this case, an IT vacuum gets filed by ‚Äúshadow IT.‚Äù

name: David Sacks
tweet: 2/ Bottom-up is still the best way into enterprises for startups. If Slack had to sell top-down, they wouldn‚Äôt have gotten anywhere. Especially true for products whose advantage is usability, rather than checkboxes. ‚ÄúShow, not tell‚Äù. Proof of the pudding is in the eating of it.

name: David Sacks

name: David Sacks

name: David Sacks
tweet: 7/ Since OTE is 20% of sales, the fully-loaded cost of an AE will represent 25% cost of sales. Sales overhead will typically cost another 15-25% of sales. That means you can spend about 50% of New ARR on Marketing CAC (lead gen) and still keep your payback under 12 months.

name: David Sacks
tweet: 6/ If an AE is unable to generate at least $400k/year in New ARR (implying $80k-100k OTEs), a sales-driven distribution strategy may not pencil.

name: David Sacks
tweet:
5/ ‚ÄúQuota Capacity‚Äù refers to the total team quota. For example, 10 AEs with quotas of $500k each = $5M QC. 

Avg team attains about 70% of QC. 

A manager‚Äôs quota should be set at 80% of QC. 

If the team is hitting 80%+ of QC, that‚Äôs a sign you can hire more AEs.

name: David Sacks
tweet:

name: David Sacks
tweet: 3/ Taken together, these standards generate a third rule: the typical quota will equal 10x base salary. I call this the Rule of 10. This generates the following pay scale for AEs: https://t.co/vgQhWVpWml

name: David Sacks
tweet:

name: David Sacks
tweet:
Consumer is tough
Because churn rates are high
Which means LTV is low
Which means CAC must be very low
Which means that growth must be organic/viral 
Which generally requires new platforms or other viral vectors
Which are rare. 

But magical when it happens.

tweet: Narrative violation: most of the returns in VC are from momentum investing, rather than contrarian investing. It‚Äôs easier to bet that the fastest growing things will continue to accrue disproportionate value than to pick winners that everyone else thinks will fail.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Happy to see one of my seed investments that raised a big SoftBank round tightening its belt. Raising from SoftBank is not the problem; assuming there will always be a bigger better round is. SoftBank-backed startups would be wise to get cashflow positive on that money.

name: David Sacks
tweet: Inter-company network effects are the holy grail for B2B SaaS apps. Once business partners are connected, it‚Äôs impossible to get ripped out. First make sure your customer‚Äôs employees are happy but then figure out how to connect their business partners.
